00:08:11.559 --> 00:08:19.239
younger writers, the big thing I always would tell them is you have to answer two questions.

00:08:19.239 --> 00:08:27.559
So what? Who cares? And that's with everything. That's really with everything. And the journalism

00:08:27.559 --> 00:08:32.359
things about you need to grab someone early. You have to have a good headline and a good lead

00:08:32.359 --> 00:08:39.239
paragraph because people have the attention spans of a gnat. I started my career in the print days

00:08:39.880 --> 00:08:47.000
when you had page one of what we would call above the fold. It was sitting there on the newsstand

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:52.440
or in the machine. And you needed to grab people if they wanted to take money out of their pocket.

00:08:52.440 --> 00:08:57.320
I mean, it's kind of the same online. It's not that different. You need a good headline and a

00:08:57.320 --> 00:09:06.440
good description. And it's the same with data. I learned early, we would be in page one pitch

00:09:06.440 --> 00:09:12.039
meetings, the daily page one, and you'd have to make your pitch to the editor who's like

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:20.119
the overall editor who was just not as immersed in this cool thing. And they call that an elevator

00:09:20.119 --> 00:09:25.960
pitch now or whatever. But I mean, you have to be, if you can't say it in three sentences about why

00:09:25.960 --> 00:09:30.840
this is cool and interesting, then go back and do it again. I mean, that's just kind of the things

00:09:30.840 --> 00:09:36.760
you learn as a writer. And it is the same thing with telling stories with data. And I needed

00:09:36.760 --> 00:09:40.599
help with people to make that connection because somehow I was not doing that when I started

00:09:40.599 --> 00:09:46.280
doing data stuff. It's like, wow, look at all this cool data. Wouldn't everyone want to spend

00:09:46.280 --> 00:09:50.440
half an hour and dive into that? Yeah, they don't. So, you know.

